data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or `ThreadAbortException`. The APIs it does use — `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — work identically on .NET 8. **No migration is needed.**

That said, this pattern can be modernized. Consider replacing raw threads with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.WhenAll` for cleaner, more efficient code:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
    {
        await Task.Delay(100, ct);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

This gives you built-in cancellation support via `CancellationToken` if you need it later.
